##Diary of the Infected Area I

Micro signal

Function description, we are with you in this battle

Wake up in the morning, subconsciously touch the bedside thermometer. 36.1, thank God. I got one more day.

To Wuhan on the 10th, I started from fearless to superstition, this year's red underwear also put on. Not of being one in one hundred thousand, but of the futility of the sacrifice, and of the disaster having one less person to remember.

The day before yesterday, the day after Dr. Li Wenliang left, I went to the Central Hospital.

On the wall of the small garden were black-and-white photographs of Dr. Li. Wreaths and flower baskets were piled on the ground. Some wrote, "a hero walks well. " Others wrote, "you are not a hero. You are just an ordinary person who stands up for himself. " Some people wrote, "abandon medicine in the next life to become enlightened people, " and some people wrote, "how the damned people are not dead. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Wreaths and baskets

It was getting dark, and some strange man put a little light on the flowers. He said that the Internet users entrusted to pay their respects, can not light a candle, light a small lamp is good. A small garden leads to the Central Hospital's Hospital building, several full-body protective clothing of the medical staff came out, standing up, with a mobile phone photo.

As I walked outside, there were still people at the door of the emergency room talking on the phone with CT scans, and people staring off into space. Hankou funeral home car and ambulance passed each other, a bouquet of lilies and several finished ramen buckets beside the fence.

It's a hospital emergency. You have to be sad every time you go.

The ICU nurse friend that sees a habit of living and dying says, "this is the world purgatory" . It's not the death itself that's angry and angry. But so many people, clearly have a chance of life, clearly have a glimmer of hope, but there is no way and resources to work.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The critical patient in the ambulance

There are two more patients to take the remaining seats, and the family members who can't travel without a car

In the face of disaster, the black hole of human nature magnifies infinitely. I've seen too much ruthlessness and futility. In the end, there's nothing I can do. Life and dignity are cheap, only beds are.

Whose fault is that?

"Wuhan Strong" for the city experienced personal pain of people, why not eat meat mince bitter feeling.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
China must win! Go, Wuhan

In ten days, I've seen five bodies taken from my sight.

Young and I like the girls, before the city is still in the purchase of New Year goods, plans to tell the family boyfriend, ready to marry the girl, overnight family death. Obviously oneself also is about to fall of the person, insist on one breath, "I dare not take my mother's life to play a joke" .

Every time I see "Wuhan Refueling" , I am very angry, this is the game, to cheer useful? It's a fucking body count.

After the death of my first subject, I didn't want to do it.

I don't know what my job means, but making a documentary might make me happier than ordering hot water for untended dads in the emergency room and handing out masks to unmasked scavengers on the road.

The instructor said there was no way. Someone had to do it. No one remembers the disaster. How can that be.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
All the departments have been converted to infection

Tell me something good.

A medical team was stationed at the hotel where I stayed, and after ten days of instant noodles, I finally got a meal. He was often treated as a nurse in the elevator because his dog chewed on his short hair. Yesterday, when I went downstairs, I was encouraged by a doctor who led the team. "wear more clothes and eat more before you have strength. ".

The walled city of Wuhan is akin to a civil society in which everyone trusts strangers unconditionally.

Over the past 10 days, I've received so much help and kindness from strangers. That day, I tried to get some medical oxygen for my severely ill interviewee. I went to several hospitals with an oxygen bag and was turned away. Finally, I met a nurse, when I mentioned that I couldn't get an ambulance, he immediately pulled me to one side of the observation room and shut the door. "I'll give you oxygen. Don't let anyone see you. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The Moon on the 15-yuan Lantern Festival in Wuhan

This is a city full of good intentions.

The people of Wuhan are in great danger.

They didn't deserve this.
